In .NET 10 (and late .NET 9), Android runs in **edge-to-edge** mode by default, which makes `adjustResize` ineffective. You now need to react to **IME window insets** instead.

**Recommended approach** — add bottom padding equal to the keyboard height using a platform-specific behavior:

```csharp
// Platforms/Android/KeyboardInsetBehavior.cs
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using Microsoft.Maui.Platform;

namespace YourApp.Platforms.Android;

public static class KeyboardInsetBehavior
{
    public static void Attach(Microsoft.Maui.Controls.Page page)
    {
        page.HandlerChanged += (s, e) =>
        {
            if (page.Handler?.PlatformView is global::Android.Views.View view)
            {
                ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(view, new InsetListener(page));
            }
        };
    }

    private class InsetListener(Microsoft.Maui.Controls.Page page)
        : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(
            global::Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

            // Use the larger of IME or nav bar so content is always visible
            var bottom = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom);
            var density = v.Context?.Resources?.DisplayMetrics?.Density ?? 1;

            page.Padding = new Thickness(0, 0, 0, bottom / density);

            return insets;
        }
    }
}
```

Then in your chat page:

```csharp
public ChatPage()
{
    InitializeComponent();

#if ANDROID
    Platforms.Android.KeyboardInsetBehavior.Attach(this);
#endif
}
```

**Why this works**: Edge-to-edge means your app draws behind system bars and the keyboard. The IME inset tells you exactly how tall the keyboard is, so you pad your layout upward by that amount.

**Alternative (quick fix)**: You can disable edge-to-edge to restore .NET 9 behavior in `MainActivity.cs`:

```csharp
protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
{
    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);
    AndroidX.Core.View.ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(
        Window!.DecorView, null);
    Window.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(true); // disables edge-to-edge
}
```

This restores `adjustResize` behavior but opts you out of modern Android UI guidelines. The insets approach is preferred long-term.
